<div id="review_2025749483" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2025749483" />
    <a title="MH" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52012221-mh"><img alt="MH" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471445670p2/52012221.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2025749483?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="MH" class="user" itemprop="url" name="MH" href="/user/show/52012221-mh">MH</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780394516660" href="/book/show/2614972-the-collected-stories-of-elizabeth-bowen">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2025749483" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17876050106368926399">Almost eighty short stories spanning four decades. Bowen writes with precision and an eye for telling details, largely of domestic spaces where the closely-described settings reflect their inhabitants, often couples who, through culture, custom, or cowardice, can&apos;t be completely honest with one another or themselves; children who are trying to make sense of their world or each other; and women, some selfish, some sweet, who commit small (and large) cruelties or find themselves trapped and lonely</span>
  <span id="freeText17876050106368926399" style="display:none">Almost eighty short stories spanning four decades. Bowen writes with precision and an eye for telling details, largely of domestic spaces where the closely-described settings reflect their inhabitants, often couples who, through culture, custom, or cowardice, can't be completely honest with one another or themselves; children who are trying to make sense of their world or each other; and women, some selfish, some sweet, who commit small (and large) cruelties or find themselves trapped and lonely. They're sad stories, mostly, but with enough small kindnesses and hopeful endings to keep her work from being a total misery. There are a handful of stylistic experiments - even one science fiction story - that didn't work for me, and her earliest writing is mannered and a little thin, but her stories from the twenties are great (especially "Anna Lee") and the thirties felt like one masterpiece after another. This collection is a massive undertaking, but wholly worthwhile.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17876050106368926399" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

