<div id="review_602527933" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/602527933" />
    <a title="Karen Barnacle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3896744-karen-barnacle"><img alt="Karen Barnacle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1370500723p2/3896744.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/602527933?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karen Barnacle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karen Barnacle" href="/user/show/3896744-karen-barnacle">Karen Barnacle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400096565" href="/book/show/195986.The_Collected_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer602527933" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11721994397479879111">These are small, sharp and glittering stories which capture the pettiness and cruelty of the upper classes in the early 20th century. It took a little while to adjust to the style and vocabulary of that era (much as it does when reading Jane Austen), but the stories really are worth this (minor) effort. There is poignancy, comedy and malice - often in the same story. They are short - sometimes only a couple of pages and the slip down like fresh oysters. I am looking forward to reading more Eliza</span>
  <span id="freeText11721994397479879111" style="display:none">These are small, sharp and glittering stories which capture the pettiness and cruelty of the upper classes in the early 20th century. It took a little while to adjust to the style and vocabulary of that era (much as it does when reading Jane Austen), but the stories really are worth this (minor) effort. There is poignancy, comedy and malice - often in the same story. They are short - sometimes only a couple of pages and the slip down like fresh oysters. I am looking forward to reading more Elizabeth Bowen.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11721994397479879111" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


